{{ 'dev-journal-cards.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}

{%- comment -%}
  Section: "Journal cards" (dev name `journal-cards`).
  Figma layer: "Image and Text" — desktop 45081:9314, mobile 44847:1162.
  Page: Our Story (NOT the homepage).

  No JS. The Brief's Interactivity section is "none": three static cards, a row on desktop and a
  plain stack on mobile. The desktop→mobile change is a CSS breakpoint reflow, NOT a slider —
  confirmed by identical block content and order on both artboards. Do not add a carousel here.

  BACKGROUND — read before "fixing" this.
  The section frame in Figma carries NO fill. The cream tone in the screenshot is the page canvas
  (#FFFCF4) showing through, not this section's own background. `background_color` therefore
  defaults to transparent (rgba(0,0,0,0)) and the section inherits the page. Painting a cream hex
  on the root would double-paint the canvas and is exactly the "read the value, don't guess it"
  trap the Brief calls out.

  BADGE BACKGROUND — the one value the Brief did not carry.
  The Brief tokenised the badge TEXT colour (#000000, distinct from --color #333333) but listed no
  badge background. Rather than invent one, it was read back off the Figma node: every _Master
  Badges instance (45081:9323 / 9333 / 9342) is `bg-[rgba(255,255,255,0.9)]` — a 90% white scrim,
  which is what keeps "Guest Review" legible over a photo. That measured value is used below.

  BADGE CORNER — 4px on the BOTTOM-RIGHT only (`rounded-br`), not all four corners.
  The badge sits flush in the top-left of the image. Its other three corners are not square by
  accident: the media wrapper is `overflow: hidden` with a 16px radius, so the badge's top-left is
  clipped by the image's own rounding. That is how Figma composes it (clip-path, rx=16) and why the
  badge only ever declares one radius.

  ZERO BOTTOM PADDING is measured, not forgotten.
  Desktop frame = 494.17px = 80px top spacer + 414.17px content, no remainder; the mobile frame has
  no bottom spacer either. This file's convention is "top spacer only, the next section supplies the
  gap". --pb defaults to 0 on purpose — QA should assert 0, not symmetry with --pt.

  CARD HEADLINE is 20px on BOTH breakpoints. The variable is named "Mobile/Title 4" in the Figma
  library, but get_variable_defs returns that same token on the desktop node too. The name is
  mislabelled upstream; the value is uniform. There is no "Desktop/Title 4" to go looking for.

  ARROW ICON — inlined verbatim from .figma-assets/journal-cards/cta-icon-arrow-right.svg.
  The `d` is byte-for-byte the owner's export; only `stroke` was swapped to `currentColor` so the
  arrow tracks --color. The viewBox origin (99 0) is a crop window onto the button's 123x24 export,
  which is how the icon resolves in-context — it isolates the 24x24 icon WITHOUT touching a single
  coordinate in `d`. Rendered box 24x24 == viewBox 24x24, so the aspect is 1:1 and nothing is
  drawn at half scale. Verified by `node .claude/tools/svg-fidelity.mjs --section journal-cards`.
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- comment -%} Fixed design tokens from Figma — not merchant-controlled {%- endcomment -%}
<style>
  .journal-cards {
    /* Brand params (Brief → Brand Params). Faces are loaded by snippets/dev-brand-fonts.liquid. */
    --font-body: 'Public Sans', sans-serif;
    --font-heading: 'Test Tiempos Headline', serif;
    /* The Figma content frame is 1440 − 2×64 = 1312, i.e. it is the section's padding box, not an
       independent cap. Per the Brief's container caveat this is 100%, not a hardcoded 1312px. */
    --container-max: 100%;
    --section-px: 64px;
    --section-px-m: 16px;

    /* Typography — desktop */
    --font-heading-size: 32px;
    --font-heading-weight: 500;
    --font-heading-lh: 1.2;
    --font-body-size: 14px;
    --font-body-weight: 400;
    --font-body-lh: 1.4;

    /* Typography — mobile: read off the Mobile artboard, not a scale factor. */
    --font-heading-size-m: 24px;
    --font-body-size-m: 12px;

    /* Card */
    --card-heading-size: 20px;
    --card-heading-weight: 500;
    --card-heading-lh: 1.2;
    --card-image-h: 220px;
    --card-image-h-m: 150px;
    --card-content-py: 16px;
    --radius-card: 16px;

    /* Badge */
    --badge-bg: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.9);
    --badge-color: #000000;
    --badge-font-size: 13px;
    --badge-font-weight: 500;
    --badge-lh: 1.4;
    --badge-px: 12px;
    --badge-py: 6px;
    --radius-badge: 4px;

    /* CTA */
    --cta-font-size: 16px;
    --cta-font-weight: 700;
    --cta-lh: 1.4;
    --cta-icon-gap: 4px;
    --cta-icon-size: 24px;

    /* Spacing */
    --spacing-sm: 12px;
    --spacing-md: 24px;
    --spacing-lg: 32px;
    --spacing-md-m: 16px;
    --spacing-lg-m: 24px;
  }
</style>

<div
  class="journal-cards"
  style="
    --bg: {{ section.settings.background_color }};
    --color: {{ section.settings.text_color }};
    --accent: {{ section.settings.accent_color }};
    --pt: {{ section.settings.padding_top }}px;
    --pb: {{ section.settings.padding_bottom }}px;
  "
>
  {%- liquid
    comment
      TWO SOURCES, ONE CARD.

      Pick a blog in the section settings and the cards become REAL articles — title, image, tag,
      author and URL all come from Shopify, so publishing a post updates the page and nobody has to
      retype "The coded language of bedding" into a theme setting ever again.

      The hand-authored blocks stay as the fallback, and that is not dead code:
        * a merchant who has not created a blog yet still gets a rendered section
        * the theme editor needs SOMETHING to show while the blog is being chosen
        * `blog.articles` is empty on a brand-new blog, and an empty section is worse than a stub
      So: blog mode when a blog is chosen AND it actually has articles; blocks otherwise.

      Both paths render snippets/dev-journal-cards-card.liquid, so the markup cannot drift.
    endcomment

    assign journal_blog = blogs[section.settings.blog]
    assign use_blog = false
    if section.settings.blog != blank and journal_blog.articles_count > 0
      assign use_blog = true
    endif
  -%}

  <div class="journal-cards__inner">
    {%- if section.settings.heading != blank -%}
      <h2 class="journal-cards__heading">{{ section.settings.heading }}</h2>
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- if use_blog -%}
      <ul class="journal-cards__list" role="list">
        {%- for article in journal_blog.articles limit: section.settings.articles_count -%}
          {%- comment -%}
            Reading time comes from snippets/dev-article-read-time.liquid, which the article page
            renders through too — so the number on the card and the number on the post it links to
            can never disagree. The snippet prefers the `custom.reading_time` metafield and falls
            back to the article's word count.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          {%- capture read_minutes -%}{%- render 'dev-article-read-time', article: article -%}{%- endcapture -%}

          {%- liquid
            # "4 min read ㆍBy Reuven S" — the separator is the artboard's own glyph, so it is
            # design, not copy, and stays here rather than in a setting.
            assign card_meta = read_minutes | append: ' ' | append: section.settings.read_time_label
            if article.author != blank
              assign card_meta = card_meta | append: ' ㆍ' | append: section.settings.author_prefix | append: ' ' | append: article.author
            endif

            # The badge is the article's FIRST tag ("Guest Review", "Insight", "Expert Guide" on the
            # artboard are exactly that shape). No tag, no badge — inventing one would be inventing
            # editorial.
            assign card_badge = article.tags | first

            assign card_alt = article.image.alt | default: article.title | escape
          -%}

          {%- render 'dev-journal-cards-card',
            image: article.image,
            image_alt: card_alt,
            badge: card_badge,
            meta: card_meta,
            heading: article.title | escape,
            url: article.url,
            cta_label: section.settings.button_label
          -%}
        {%- endfor -%}
      </ul>

    {%- elsif section.blocks.size > 0 -%}
      <ul class="journal-cards__list" role="list">
        {%- for block in section.blocks -%}
          {%- assign card_alt = block.settings.image.alt | default: block.settings.heading | strip_html | escape -%}

          {%- render 'dev-journal-cards-card',
            image: block.settings.image,
            image_alt: card_alt,
            badge: block.settings.badge_label,
            meta: block.settings.meta_text,
            heading: block.settings.heading,
            url: block.settings.button_link,
            cta_label: block.settings.button_label,
            attrs: block.shopify_attributes
          -%}
        {%- endfor -%}
      </ul>
    {%- endif -%}
  </div>
</div>

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "Journal cards",
  "tag": "section",
  "settings": [
    { "type": "header", "content": "Content" },
    {
      "type": "inline_richtext",
      "id": "heading",
      "label": "Heading",
      "default": "The coded language of bedding — Uncoded"
    },

    { "type": "header", "content": "Articles" },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Pick a blog and the cards become real articles — image, title, tag, author and link all come from Shopify. Leave it empty to hand-author the cards as blocks instead."
    },
    { "type": "blog", "id": "blog", "label": "Blog" },
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "articles_count",
      "min": 1,
      "max": 6,
      "step": 1,
      "label": "Articles to show",
      "info": "The design lays out three across; more will wrap.",
      "default": 3
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "id": "button_label",
      "label": "Card link label",
      "info": "Used for every article card. Hand-authored blocks keep their own label.",
      "default": "Read Article"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "id": "read_time_label",
      "label": "Reading time label",
      "info": "Reading time is estimated from the article's own word count at 200 words per minute.",
      "default": "min read"
    },
    { "type": "text", "id": "author_prefix", "label": "Author prefix", "default": "By" },

    { "type": "header", "content": "Colors" },
    {
      "type": "color",
      "id": "background_color",
      "label": "Background",
      "info": "Transparent by default — the design has no fill here and inherits the page background.",
      "default": "rgba(0,0,0,0)"
    },
    { "type": "color", "id": "text_color", "label": "Text color", "default": "#333333" },
    {
      "type": "color",
      "id": "accent_color",
      "label": "Accent color",
      "info": "Used for focus outlines. The design has no accent distinct from the text colour.",
      "default": "#333333"
    },

    { "type": "header", "content": "Spacing" },
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "padding_top",
      "min": 0,
      "max": 200,
      "step": 4,
      "unit": "px",
      "label": "Padding top",
      "info": "Halved on mobile (80 → 40), matching the mobile artboard.",
      "default": 80
    },
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "padding_bottom",
      "min": 0,
      "max": 200,
      "step": 4,
      "unit": "px",
      "label": "Padding bottom",
      "info": "The design has no bottom spacer — the next section supplies the gap.",
      "default": 0
    }
  ],
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "journal_card",
      "name": "Journal card",
      "limit": 3,
      "settings": [
        { "type": "image_picker", "id": "image", "label": "Image" },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "id": "badge_label",
          "label": "Badge label",
          "info": "Small overlay label on the image, e.g. \"Guest Review\".",
          "default": "Guest Review"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "id": "meta_text",
          "label": "Meta text",
          "info": "Shown in uppercase automatically — type it normally.",
          "default": "4 min read ㆍBy Priya s"
        },
        {
          "type": "inline_richtext",
          "id": "heading",
          "label": "Article title",
          "default": "My first night using the tree-mendous duvet"
        },
        { "type": "text", "id": "button_label", "label": "Button label", "default": "Read Article" },
        { "type": "url", "id": "button_link", "label": "Button link" }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "max_blocks": 3,
  "presets": [
    {
      "name": "Journal cards",
      "blocks": [
        { "type": "journal_card" },
        { "type": "journal_card" },
        { "type": "journal_card" }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
{% endschema %}
